# ============================================================================
# Sensationalism Worldview - Value Hierarchy
# ============================================================================
#
# Philosophical Foundation:
# - Reality is fundamentally qualitative sensory experience
# - Knowledge derives from immediate felt qualities (qualia)
# - Epistemology: Direct sensory intuition, phenomenal immediacy
# - Values grounded in experiential richness and aesthetic beauty
#
# Primary Sources:
# - Hume, D. (1739-40). A Treatise of Human Nature. Oxford University Press.
# - Berkeley, G. (1710). A Treatise Concerning the Principles of Human Knowledge.
# - Condillac, É. B. de. (1754). Treatise on Sensations (Traité des sensations).
# - Mach, E. (1886). The Analysis of Sensations and the Relation of the Physical to the Psychical.
# - James, W. (1890). The Principles of Psychology. Henry Holt and Company.
#
# Contemporary Empirical Research:
# - Chatterjee, A. (2011). Neuroaesthetics: A Coming of Age Story. Journal of Cognitive Neuroscience, 23(1), 53-62.
# - Kahneman, D., Wakker, P. P., & Sarin, R. (1997). Back to Bentham? Explorations of experienced utility. Quarterly Journal of Economics, 112(2), 375-406.
# - Goldstone, R. L. (1998). Perceptual Learning. Annual Review of Psychology, 49, 585-612.
# - Nadal, M., & Pearce, M. T. (2011). The Copenhagen Neuroaesthetics Conference. Brain and Cognition, 76(1), 1-4.
# - Leder, H., et al. (2004). A model of aesthetic appreciation and aesthetic judgments. British Journal of Psychology, 95(4), 489-508.
#
# Key Distinction from Materialism:
# - Materialism: Physical substrate is real, experience is derivative
# - Sensationalism: Experience/sensation is real, physical substrate inferred
#
# Key Distinction from Phenomenalism:
# - Phenomenalism: Focuses on validity of appearances (epistemic)
# - Sensationalism: Focuses on quality of sensations (axiological)
#
# Key Distinction from Rationalism:
# - Rationalism: Abstract logical relations are fundamental
# - Sensationalism: Immediate sensory impressions are fundamental
#   (Hume's distinction: impressions have greater vivacity than ideas)
#
# This ontology uses BFO/CCO patterns and integrates with ValueNet to
# model how sensationalist metaphysics grounds specific value hierarchies
# and maps to value dispositions.
#
# ============================================================================
# BIBLIOGRAPHIC CITATIONS
# ============================================================================
#
# Primary Philosophical Sources:
# - Hume, D. (1739-40). A Treatise of Human Nature. Book I: Of the Understanding. Oxford University Press (2000 ed.).
# - Berkeley, G. (1710). A Treatise Concerning the Principles of Human Knowledge. Aaron Rhames.
# - Condillac, É. B. de. (1754). Treatise on Sensations (Traité des sensations). Trans. Geraldine Carr. Los Angeles: University of Southern California (1930).
# - Mach, E. (1886). The Analysis of Sensations and the Relation of the Physical to the Psychical. Trans. C. M. Williams. Chicago: Open Court (1914).
# - James, W. (1890). The Principles of Psychology. Vol. 1-2. Henry Holt and Company.
# - Mill, J. S. (1865). An Examination of Sir William Hamilton's Philosophy. Longmans, Green.
#
# Empirical Research - Neuroaesthetics:
# - Chatterjee, A. (2011). Neuroaesthetics: A Coming of Age Story. Journal of Cognitive Neuroscience, 23(1), 53-62.
# - Nadal, M., & Pearce, M. T. (2011). The Copenhagen Neuroaesthetics Conference: Prospects and pitfalls for an emerging field. Brain and Cognition, 76(1), 1-4.
# - Leder, H., Belke, B., Oeberst, A., & Augustin, D. (2004). A model of aesthetic appreciation and aesthetic judgments. British Journal of Psychology, 95(4), 489-508.
# - Vessel, E. A., Starr, G. G., & Rubin, N. (2012). The brain on art: intense aesthetic experience activates the default mode network. Frontiers in Human Neuroscience, 6, 66.
#
# Empirical Research - Hedonic Psychology:
# - Kahneman, D., Wakker, P. P., & Sarin, R. (1997). Back to Bentham? Explorations of experienced utility. Quarterly Journal of Economics, 112(2), 375-406.
# - Kahneman, D., Fredrickson, B. L., Schreiber, C. A., & Redelmeier, D. A. (1993). When More Pain Is Preferred to Less: Adding a Better End. Psychological Science, 4(6), 401-405.
# - Fredrickson, B. L., & Kahneman, D. (1993). Duration neglect in retrospective evaluations of affective episodes. Journal of Personality and Social Psychology, 65(1), 45-55.
#
# Empirical Research - Perceptual Learning:
# - Goldstone, R. L. (1998). Perceptual Learning. Annual Review of Psychology, 49, 585-612.
# - Gibson, E. J. (1969). Principles of Perceptual Learning and Development. Appleton-Century-Crofts.
# - Fahle, M., & Poggio, T. (Eds.). (2002). Perceptual Learning. MIT Press.
# ============================================================================

# ============================================================================
# WORLDVIEW DEFINITION
# ============================================================================

:Sensationalism a :Worldview ;
    :name "sensationalism" ;
    :foundation "sensory_experience" ;
    :primacy "qualitative_immediacy" ;
    :epistemology "direct_sensory_intuition" ;
    :cluster :MaterialEmpirical ;
    dcterms:source "Hume (1739), Berkeley (1710), Condillac (1754)" ;
    rdfs:comment "Worldview grounding value in immediate sensory experience and qualitative richness." ;
    skos:definition "The metaphysical position that reality is constituted by sensory experiences and their qualitative properties, and that value derives from experiential intensity and aesthetic quality. 'Esse est percipi' (Berkeley): to be is to be perceived." .

# ============================================================================
# TERMINAL VALUES - Highest Goods in Sensationalist Framework
# ============================================================================

:SensoryExperience a :TerminalValue ;
    :groundedIn :Sensationalism ;
    :primacy "ultimate" ;
    :manifestsAs :PleasurableSensation, :AestheticEncounter, :SensoryRichness ;
    dcterms:source "Hume (1739) Book I, Part I: 'All our simple ideas in their first appearance are derived from simple impressions, which are correspondent to them, and which they exactly represent.'" ;
    :empiricalEvidence "Chatterjee (2011): Neural correlates of aesthetic experience involve ventral striatum (reward) and medial orbitofrontal cortex (valuation)" ;
    rdfs:comment "Sensory experience is the terminal good because sensationalism grounds all reality in immediate felt qualities (Hume's 'impressions')." ;
    skos:definition "The richness and intensity of immediate sensory encounters, valued as the fundamental good from which all other values derive." .

:AestheticPleasure a :TerminalValue ;
    :groundedIn :Sensationalism ;
    :manifestsAs :BeautyExperience, :HarmonicSensation, :ArtisticEncounter ;
    :requires :SensoryRefinement, :AestheticCultivation ;
    dcterms:source "Hume, D. (1757). Of the Standard of Taste. In Essays, Moral, Political, and Literary." ;
    :empiricalEvidence "Leder et al. (2004): Aesthetic appreciation involves perceptual analysis, implicit memory integration, explicit classification, and cognitive mastery stages." ;
    rdfs:comment "Aesthetic pleasure combines sensory intensity with harmonic form, representing cultivated sensationalism. Hume's 'delicacy of taste' requires both natural sensitivity and practice." ;
    skos:definition "The experience of beauty through refined sensory perception, valued as a higher form of experiential quality." .

:ExperientialIntensity a :TerminalValue ;
    :groundedIn :Sensationalism ;
    :measuredBy :QualitativeDensity, :SensoryVividness ;
    :manifestsAs :RichExperience, :HeightenedAwareness ;
    dcterms:source "Hume (1739) Book I, Part I, Section I: 'Those perceptions, which enter with most force and violence, we may name impressions... By ideas I mean the faint images of these in thinking and reasoning.'" ;
    :empiricalEvidence "Kahneman et al. (1993): Peak-end rule demonstrates that intensity of experience dominates duration in retrospective evaluations" ;
    rdfs:comment "Not mere quantity of sensation, but qualitative intensity and vividness of experience. Hume's 'force and vivacity' distinguish impressions from ideas." ;
    skos:definition "The degree of qualitative richness and vividness in sensory experience, independent of duration or quantity." .

# ============================================================================
# CONSTITUTIVE VALUES - Essential Components of Terminal Values
# ============================================================================

:PleasurableSensation a :ConstitutiveValue ;
    :constitutes :SensoryExperience ;
    :manifestsAs :HedonicFeeling, :AgreeableQuality ;
    :measuredBy :PleasureIntensity ;
    dcterms:source "Hume (1739) Book II: 'Pleasure and pain are not only necessary attendants of beauty and deformity, but constitute their very essence.'" ;
    :empiricalEvidence "Kahneman et al. (1997): Experienced utility (moment-to-moment hedonic states) distinct from decision utility. Sensationalism prioritizes experienced utility." ;
    :psychologicalPhenomenon :PeakEndRule, :HedonicAdaptation ;
    rdfs:comment "Pleasure as immediate hedonic quality of sensation (Hume's 'impressions of pleasure'), not as utility or consequence." .

:SensoryRichness a :ConstitutiveValue ;
    :constitutes :SensoryExperience ;
    :manifestsAs :ComplexQualia, :LayeredExperience ;
    :includes :VisualRichness, :AuditoryDepth, :TactileComplexity, :GustatoryNuance, :OlfactorySubtlety ;
    dcterms:source "James (1890) Vol. 1, Ch. VII: 'The baby, assailed by eyes, ears, nose, skin, and entrails at once, feels it all as one great blooming, buzzing confusion.'" ;
    :empiricalEvidence "Goldstone (1998): Perceptual learning involves differentiation (detecting new features) and unitization (forming new perceptual units)" ;
    rdfs:comment "Complexity and multi-layered quality of sensory experience. Refined through perceptual learning (Goldstone 1998)." .

:AestheticRefinement a :ConstitutiveValue ;
    :constitutes :AestheticPleasure ;
    :requires :CultivatedTaste, :SensoryEducation ;
    :manifestsAs :DiscriminatingPerception ;
    dcterms:source "Hume (1757) 'Of the Standard of Taste': 'Strong sense, united to delicate sentiment, improved by practice, perfected by comparison, and cleared of all prejudice, can alone entitle critics to this valuable character.'" ;
    :empiricalEvidence "Goldstone (1998): Wine experts show enhanced discrimination in gustatory and olfactory dimensions through perceptual learning" ;
    rdfs:comment "Capacity to perceive subtle aesthetic qualities through refined sensory faculties. Hume's 'delicacy of taste' emerges from practice and comparison." .

:SensoryClarity a :ConstitutiveValue ;
    :constitutes :ExperientialIntensity ;
    :manifestsAs :VividPerception, :UncloudedAwareness ;
    :opposedTo :SensoryDullness, :NumbedPerception ;
    dcterms:source "Hume (1739) Book I, Part I, Section I: Impressions have greater 'force and vivacity' than ideas" ;
    :empiricalEvidence "Attention enhances sensory processing: Kastner & Ungerleider (2000). Mechanisms of visual attention in the human cortex. Annual Review of Neuroscience, 23, 315-341." ;
    rdfs:comment "Clarity and vividness of sensory perception, heightened awareness. Cultivated through attentional focus." .

# ============================================================================
# INSTRUMENTAL VALUES - Means to Terminal Values
# ============================================================================

:Art a :InstrumentalValue ;
    :servesValue :AestheticPleasure, :SensoryRichness ;
    :manifestsAs :VisualArt, :Music, :Dance, :Poetry, :Sculpture ;
    :purpose "Creates opportunities for refined sensory experience" ;
    dcterms:source "Kant, I. (1790). Critique of Judgment. Trans. Werner Pluhar. Hackett (1987)." ;
    :empiricalEvidence "Vessel et al. (2012): Intensely aesthetic experiences activate default mode network, suggesting personal relevance and self-referential processing" ;
    rdfs:comment "Art as primary instrument for cultivating aesthetic sensory experience. Provides structured opportunities for refined perception." .

:SensoryCultivation a :InstrumentalValue ;
    :servesValue :AestheticRefinement, :SensoryClarity ;
    :manifestsAs :TasteEducation, :PerceptualTraining ;
    :includes :WineAppreciation, :MusicTraining, :ArtEducation, :CulinaryRefinement ;
    dcterms:source "Hume (1757): 'Nothing tends further to encrease and improve this talent, than practice in a particular art, and the frequent survey or contemplation of a particular species of beauty.'" ;
    :empiricalEvidence "Goldstone (1998): Perceptual learning shows specificity to trained stimuli and transfer to similar domains" ;
    rdfs:comment "Practices that refine and heighten sensory discrimination. Empirically validated through perceptual learning research." .

:Aesthetics a :InstrumentalValue ;
    :servesValue :AestheticPleasure, :ExperientialIntensity ;
    :manifestsAs :BeautyTheory, :ArtisticPrinciples ;
    dcterms:source "Burke, E. (1757). A Philosophical Enquiry into the Origin of Our Ideas of the Sublime and Beautiful." ;
    rdfs:comment "Study of aesthetic principles to guide sensory cultivation. Subordinate to direct experience but useful for systematic refinement." .

:SensoryEnvironment a :InstrumentalValue ;
    :servesValue :SensoryExperience, :ExperientialIntensity ;
    :manifestsAs :BeautifulSpaces, :PleasantSoundscapes, :AgreeableAromas ;
    :purpose "Optimizes environmental conditions for rich sensory experience" ;
    :empiricalEvidence "Environmental psychology: Ulrich et al. (1991). Stress recovery during exposure to natural and urban environments. Journal of Environmental Psychology, 11(3), 201-230." ;
    rdfs:comment "Cultivation of physical environments to maximize experiential quality. Empirically supported by environmental psychology." .

# ============================================================================
# SUBORDINATED VALUES - De-prioritized in Sensationalist Framework
# ============================================================================

:AbstractReasoning a :SubordinatedValue ;
    :subordinatedIn :Sensationalism ;
    :status "derived_from_impressions" ;
    :salience "very_low" ;
    dcterms:source "Hume (1739) Book I, Part III: 'All our reasonings concerning matters of fact are founded on a species of Analogy, which leads us to expect from any cause the same events, which we have observed to result from similar causes.'" ;
    :philosophicalNote "Sensationalism does NOT reduce concepts to mere words (that is nominalism). Rather, abstract ideas are derivative from sensory impressions via association (Hume's principles: resemblance, contiguity, causation). Condillac (1754) demonstrates genetic derivation: all faculties emerge from sensation through transformation." ;
    rdfs:comment "Abstract concepts derived from sensory impressions through association (Hume). Logic valued only insofar as it enhances or guides sensory experience. Not ontologically reduced to verbal sensations (that conflates sensationalism with nominalism), but genetically derived from impressions." ;
    skos:definition "Logical and abstract reasoning valued only insofar as it enhances sensory experience, not as independent truth. All abstract ideas traceable to original sensory impressions." .

:MoralPrinciples a :SubordinatedValue ;
    :subordinatedIn :Sensationalism ;
    :reducedTo :MoralSentiments ;
    :salience "low" ;
    dcterms:source "Hume (1751). An Enquiry Concerning the Principles of Morals: 'Morality is more properly felt than judg'd of.'" ;
    :distinguishedFrom "Rationalist ethics (Kant) which grounds morality in pure practical reason. Sensationalist ethics grounded in moral sentiments (sympathy, approval/disapproval)." ;
    :valuenetNote "MoralPrinciples maps differently across worldviews: Rationalism → UniversalismDisposition (universal rational principles). Sensationalism → BenevolenceDisposition (sympathetic feeling)." ;
    rdfs:comment "Moral principles subordinated to felt emotional qualities; ethics becomes aesthetics of feeling (Hume's moral sentiments). Morality grounded in sympathy and approval/disapproval (feelings), not abstract rational principles." ;
    skos:definition "Moral claims valued for their emotional/aesthetic quality (sympathy, approbation) rather than rational justification." .

:MaterialSubstrate a :SubordinatedValue ;
    :subordinatedIn :Sensationalism ;
    :status "inferred_not_given" ;
    :salience "very_low" ;
    dcterms:source "Berkeley (1710) Part I, §3: 'Esse est percipi' - to be is to be perceived. Material objects are collections of sensory ideas." ;
    :empiricalAnalogy "Modern physics (quantum mechanics) shows observation affects measured properties, resonating with sensationalist primacy of experience over substrate." ;
    rdfs:comment "Physical substrate inferred from sensations but not directly experienced; secondary to qualitative experience. Berkeley's idealism: material objects are 'permanent possibilities of sensation' (Mill 1865)." ;
    skos:definition "Material objects treated as useful constructs from sensation patterns, not as independently real substrates." .

:UtilitarianConsequences a :SubordinatedValue ;
    :subordinatedIn :Sensationalism ;
    :instrumentalizedFor :HedonicExperience ;
    :salience "low" ;
    dcterms:source "Contrasts with Bentham's utilitarian calculus. Sensationalism values experienced utility (Kahneman 1997) over calculated aggregate utility." ;
    :empiricalEvidence "Kahneman et al. (1997): Decision utility (predicted/calculated) often diverges from experienced utility (actual hedonic states). Sensationalism prioritizes experienced utility." ;
    rdfs:comment "Practical utility subordinated to immediate experiential quality; consequences valued only for their felt qualities. Rejects abstract utility calculation in favor of direct hedonic experience." ;
    skos:definition "Future consequences valued only as anticipated sensory experiences, not as abstract utilities." .

# ============================================================================
# BFO/CCO GROUNDING PATTERNS
# ============================================================================

# Sensory Quality Substrates (BFO pattern)
:HedonicQuality a bfo:0000019 ;  # quality
    bfo:0000052 :SensoryExperience ;  # inheres_in
    :hasSpecifiedValue :PleasureIntensity ;
    dcterms:source "Kahneman et al. (1997): Hedonic quality as directly experienced utility" ;
    rdfs:label "Hedonic Quality" ;
    rdfs:comment "Pleasure as quality substrate inhering in sensory experiences. Empirically measurable via experience sampling methods." .

:AestheticQuality a bfo:0000019 ;  # quality
    bfo:0000052 :AestheticObject ;  # inheres_in
    :hasSpecifiedValue :BeautyDegree ;
    :perceived_through :RefinedSensoryFaculty ;
    dcterms:source "Leder et al. (2004): Aesthetic quality emerges from multi-stage processing" ;
    rdfs:label "Aesthetic Quality" ;
    rdfs:comment "Beauty as quality substrate inhering in aesthetic objects/experiences. Requires perceptual analysis and cognitive mastery stages." .

:SensoryVividness a bfo:0000019 ;  # quality
    bfo:0000052 :Perception ;  # inheres_in
    :hasSpecifiedValue :VividnessLevel ;
    :increases_through :Attention, :Cultivation ;
    dcterms:source "Hume (1739): Vividness distinguishes impressions from ideas" ;
    rdfs:label "Sensory Vividness" ;
    rdfs:comment "Vividness as quality of perceptual experience. Hume's 'force and vivacity' as defining feature of impressions." .

# BFO Dispositions (Realizable Entities)
:SensoryDiscriminationDisposition a bfo:0000016 ;  # disposition
    bfo:0000052 :Perceiver ;  # inheres_in
    :cultivated_through :SensoryCultivationProcess ;
    dcterms:source "Goldstone (1998): Perceptual learning enhances discrimination ability" ;
    rdfs:label "Sensory Discrimination Disposition" ;
    rdfs:comment "Disposition to perceive subtle differences in sensory qualities. Enhanced through perceptual learning." .

:AestheticAppreciationDisposition a bfo:0000016 ;  # disposition
    bfo:0000052 :Perceiver ;  # inheres_in
    :requires :AestheticRefinement ;
    dcterms:source "Hume (1757): 'Delicacy of taste' as cultivated disposition" ;
    rdfs:label "Aesthetic Appreciation Disposition" ;
    rdfs:comment "Disposition to appreciate beauty and aesthetic harmony. Cultivated through practice and comparison (Hume)." .

:PleasureDisposition a bfo:0000016 ;  # disposition
    bfo:0000052 :Perceiver ;  # inheres_in
    :manifestsAs :HedonicResponse ;
    dcterms:source "Kahneman et al. (1997): Individual differences in hedonic response patterns" ;
    rdfs:label "Pleasure Disposition" ;
    rdfs:comment "Disposition to experience pleasure from sensory stimuli. Subject to hedonic adaptation and peak-end effects." .

:RefinementDisposition a bfo:0000016 ;  # disposition
    bfo:0000052 :Perceiver ;  # inheres_in
    :developed_through :Practice, :Education ;
    dcterms:source "Hume (1757): Refinement through 'practice, perfected by comparison'" ;
    rdfs:label "Refinement Disposition" ;
    rdfs:comment "Disposition toward increasingly subtle and discriminating aesthetic perception." .

# Processes that realize sensationalist values (BFO:Process)
:AestheticEncounter a bfo:0000015 ;  # process
    bfo:0000055 :AestheticAppreciationDisposition ;  # realizes (BFO relation)
    bfo:0000057 :Perceiver ;  # has_participant
    bfo:0000057 :AestheticObject ;  # has_participant
    :produces :AestheticExperience ;
    dcterms:source "Leder et al. (2004): Multi-stage model of aesthetic processing" ;
    rdfs:label "Aesthetic Encounter" ;
    rdfs:comment "Process of aesthetic appreciation realizing aesthetic value disposition. Involves perceptual analysis, memory integration, classification, and cognitive mastery stages." .

:SensoryCultivationProcess a bfo:0000015 ;  # process
    bfo:0000055 :RefinementDisposition ;  # realizes (BFO relation)
    bfo:0000057 :Student ;  # has_participant
    bfo:0000057 :Teacher ;  # has_participant
    :improves :SensoryDiscrimination ;
    :temporallyExtendedOver :TrainingPeriod ;
    dcterms:source "Goldstone (1998): Perceptual learning requires repeated exposure and feedback" ;
    rdfs:label "Sensory Cultivation Process" ;
    rdfs:comment "Process of training sensory faculties to greater discrimination and refinement. Empirically validated perceptual learning process." .

:HedonicExperienceProcess a bfo:0000015 ;  # process
    bfo:0000055 :PleasureDisposition ;  # realizes (BFO relation)
    bfo:0000057 :Experiencer ;  # has_participant
    :produces :PleasurableState ;
    dcterms:source "Kahneman et al. (1993): Hedonic experience shows peak-end rule pattern" ;
    rdfs:label "Hedonic Experience Process" ;
    rdfs:comment "Process of pleasurable sensory experience. Retrospective evaluation dominated by peak intensity and end state." .

# Information Content Entities (CCO pattern)
:AestheticTheory a cco:InformationContentEntity ;
    :describes :BeautyPrinciples ;
    :guides :SensoryCultivation ;
    :subordinate_to :DirectExperience ;
    dcterms:source "Burke (1757), Kant (1790): Systematic aesthetic theory" ;
    rdfs:label "Aesthetic Theory" ;
    rdfs:comment "Theoretical knowledge about beauty, subordinate to direct aesthetic experience but useful for guiding cultivation." .

# ============================================================================
# HUME'S ASSOCIATION PRINCIPLES - Core Sensationalist Epistemology
# ============================================================================

:AssociationOfIdeas a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:subClassOf :CognitiveProcess ;
    dcterms:source "Hume (1739) Book I, Part I, Section IV: 'The qualities, from which this association arises, and by which the mind is after this manner convey'd from one idea to another, are three, viz. RESEMBLANCE, CONTIGUITY in time or place, and CAUSE and EFFECT.'" ;
    rdfs:label "Association of Ideas" ;
    skos:definition "Hume's three principles by which simple impressions combine to form complex ideas: Resemblance, Contiguity, and Cause-Effect." ;
    :principles :Resemblance, :Contiguity, :CauseEffect .

:Resemblance a :AssociationPrinciple ;
    dcterms:source "Hume (1739) Book I, Part I, Section IV" ;
    skos:definition "Principle of association: ideas that resemble each other naturally suggest each other. Example: portrait leads mind to original person." ;
    :empiricalAnalogy "Modern prototype theory (Rosch 1975): categorization based on resemblance to prototypes" .

:Contiguity a :AssociationPrinciple ;
    dcterms:source "Hume (1739) Book I, Part I, Section IV" ;
    skos:definition "Principle of association: ideas contiguous in space or time naturally suggest each other. Example: mention of room in building suggests adjoining rooms." ;
    :empiricalAnalogy "Classical conditioning (Pavlov): association by temporal contiguity" .

:CauseEffect a :AssociationPrinciple ;
    dcterms:source "Hume (1739) Book I, Part III: 'All reasonings concerning matter of fact seem to be founded on the relation of Cause and Effect.'" ;
    skos:definition "Principle of association: ideas related as cause-effect naturally suggest each other. Example: thought of wound suggests pain. Note: Hume argues causation is ultimately reducible to constant conjunction (contiguity + repetition)." ;
    :empiricalAnalogy "Causal learning research (Shanks 2010): humans track statistical contingencies" .

:Impression a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:subClassOf :MentalContent ;
    dcterms:source "Hume (1739) Book I, Part I, Section I: 'By the term impression, then, I mean all our more lively perceptions, when we hear, or see, or feel, or love, or hate, or desire, or will.'" ;
    :hasQuality :Vividness ;
    :vividnessLevel "high" ;
    rdfs:label "Impression (Hume)" ;
    skos:definition "Immediate, vivid sensory or emotional experience. Distinguished from ideas by greater force and vivacity." ;
    :subtypes :ImpressionOfSensation, :ImpressionOfReflection .

:Idea a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:subClassOf :MentalContent ;
    dcterms:source "Hume (1739) Book I, Part I, Section I: 'By ideas I mean the faint images of these [impressions] in thinking and reasoning.'" ;
    :hasQuality :Faintness ;
    :vividnessLevel "low" ;
    :derivedFrom :Impression ;
    rdfs:label "Idea (Hume)" ;
    skos:definition "Faint copy of impression in thought or reasoning. Less vivid than original impression." .

# ============================================================================
# AESTHETIC CATEGORIES - Sensationalist Aesthetics
# ============================================================================

:Beautiful a :AestheticCategory ;
    dcterms:source "Burke (1757): Beauty produces love/positive inclination; characterized by smoothness, delicacy, gradual variation" ;
    :sensoryQualities :Smoothness, :Delicacy, :GradualVariation ;
    :emotionalResponse :Love, :Tenderness ;
    rdfs:label "Beautiful" ;
    skos:definition "Aesthetic category characterized by harmonious, smooth, delicate sensory qualities producing tender affection." .

:Sublime a :AestheticCategory ;
    dcterms:source "Burke (1757): Sublime produces awe/terror; characterized by vastness, obscurity, power. Kant (1790): Sublime involves inadequacy of imagination to comprehend magnitude/power." ;
    :sensoryQualities :Vastness, :Obscurity, :Power, :Infinity ;
    :emotionalResponse :Awe, :Terror, :Astonishment ;
    rdfs:label "Sublime" ;
    skos:definition "Aesthetic category characterized by overwhelming vastness or power producing awe and astonishment." .

:Elegant a :AestheticCategory ;
    dcterms:source "Hume (1757): Elegance combines simplicity with refinement" ;
    :sensoryQualities :Simplicity, :Refinement, :Proportion ;
    :emotionalResponse :Admiration, :Satisfaction ;
    rdfs:label "Elegant" ;
    skos:definition "Aesthetic category characterized by refined simplicity and harmonious proportion." .

# ============================================================================
# EXPANDED SENSORY MODALITY HIERARCHY
# ============================================================================

:SensoryModality a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "Sensory Modality" ;
    skos:definition "Distinct channels of sensory experience, each providing unique qualitative dimensions." ;
    dcterms:source "James (1890) Vol. 2, Ch. XVII: 'The Five Senses'" .

:Vision a :SensoryModality ;
    :qualitativeDimensions :Color, :Brightness, :Shape, :Motion, :Depth ;
    :receptorType "photoreceptors (rods and cones)" ;
    dcterms:source "James (1890): Vision provides spatial extension most directly" ;
    skos:definition "Visual sensory modality providing color, form, and spatial information." .

:Audition a :SensoryModality ;
    :qualitativeDimensions :Pitch, :Loudness, :Timbre, :Rhythm, :Harmony ;
    :receptorType "hair cells in cochlea" ;
    dcterms:source "Helmholtz, H. (1863). On the Sensations of Tone" ;
    skos:definition "Auditory sensory modality providing temporal patterns and harmonic structure." .

